"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638600","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>We have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-29T15:37:26.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638600/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638600/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-18","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the raid on the Health Development and Policy Institute in Ramallah by Israeli forces, whether they intend to make representations to the government of Israel and call for compensation for that Institute.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638601","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-02","<p>The UK is a long-term supporter of the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA), providing over £60 million in 2015/16 in Gaza, the West Bank and the region. We regularly discuss with UNRWA how it can resolve its financial situation. As a major donor, we encourage UNRWA to implement reforms to put it on a more sustainable financial footing and we press for other donor contributions.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-02T14:16:39.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638601/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638601/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","UNRWA: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the statement by the Commissioner General of the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA) to the second bi-annual UNRWA Advisory Commission meeting for 2016 held in Amman, stressing the case for UNWRA to be placed on a more stable financial footing.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL3352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638602","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-29","<p><br>To date we have established 8 working groups which have met 26 times since the passing of the Act.</p><p />",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-29T15:39:04.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638602/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638602/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-18","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many working groups have been established, and how many times each of them has met, since the passing of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638603","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-29","<p>Our public consultations on the Housing and Planning Act 2016 were open to all, including all voluntary organisations.</p><p />",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-29T15:33:45.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638603/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638603/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-18","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which voluntary sector organisations they have formally consulted on matters contained in the Housing and Planning Act 2016 since that Act came into force.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638604","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-11-28","<p>As a public authority, the Parades Commission has general obligations under public law; the discharge of those obligations is an operational matter for the Parades Commission, acting independently of Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Parades Commission determinations make regular reference to the European Convention on Human Rights. Details of all determinations are published on the Commission’s website at www.paradescommission.org.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2016-11-28T14:44:46.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638604/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638604/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-18","Parades Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 31 October (HL2454), whether the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland has the ability to make reference to human rights instruments such as the European Convention on Human Rights when making decisions.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638605","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>We are deeply concerned by the ongoing violence in South Sudan and agree with the United Nations Special Advisor on the Prevention of Genocide that the international community needs to act fast before genocide becomes a reality. Together with our regional and international partners, we continue to press both the government of South Sudan and the Opposition to show restraint and work to build peace through an inclusive political process. In parallel, as we have consistently made clear, we fully support a United Nations arms embargo on South Sudan and will continue to push for this in Security Council discussions in New York.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-29T15:38:46.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638605/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638605/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-18","South Sudan: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the publication on 15 November of the Interim Report of the UN panel of experts on South Sudan, what measures are being taken to avert the threat of genocide in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord St John of Bletso",,"Lord St John of Bletso","HL3356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638606","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>Ministers meet regularly with Ministers from Commonwealth countries, both in London and on their visits overseas. The majority of the Commonwealth's 52 members are represented by High Commissioners in London. Meetings with visiting Ministers are typically organised by High Commissioners and their staff or by High Commissioners at UK missions overseas. Where a VIP is invited to the UK by Her Majesty's Government, the visit programme is arranged through Protocol Directorate of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. We place significant importance on Ministerial meetings which provide the opportunity for discussions on a range of Commonwealth and other issues. Recently, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) had a warm and productive meeting with the Grenadian Prime Minister and St Lucian Prime Minister. Similar visits and discussions, both inwards and outwards, will become increasingly important as we look ahead to hosting the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in 2018.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-29T15:39:52.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638606/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638606/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-18","Commonwealth: Official Visits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what arrangements are in place to ensure that Government ministers are able to meet and hold discussions with ministers from Commonwealth countries, especially those from small island states, when they visit London.","false","Biography information for Baroness Taylor of Bolton",,"Baroness Taylor of Bolton","HL3357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638612","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Marriage Allowance was introduced in April 2015, to recognise the importance of marriage and provide support to those on low incomes, many of whom have little engagement with tax matters. So it is right that the Government has taken action to improve awareness of the positive impact this allowance could have on family finances. Since the introduction of the Marriage Allowance in April 2015, HM Revenue and Customs has spent £1,457,479 (excluding VAT) on targeted campaigns to raise awareness. Families across the UK could be better off by up to £432 if they claim the Marriage Allowance today if their application is backdated to April 2015.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-23T10:06:52.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638612/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638612/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-18","Married People: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on advertising the marriage tax allowance in each year since it was introduced.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","53728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638613","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>I am aware of discussions between a number of local authorities and NHS Trusts in relation to charitable business rate relief. The decision to grant charitable rate relief is taken by individual local authorities, the Department for Communities and Local Government is working closely with the Department of Health, the Local Government Association, and local government to consider the issues.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-26T14:59:27.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638613/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638613/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638613/answer/previousversion/22327","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-18","Bilfinger: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will intervene in the business rates appeal by Bilfinger GVA on behalf of NHS trusts to prevent public funds being spent on Bilfinger GVA,","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638614","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-23","<p>At the end of every tax year HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) electronically reviews all individual PAYE records to see whether or not the correct amount of tax and National Insurance Contributions for the year has been paid. Where there is an under or overpayment, HMRC notifies the individual through issuing form P800. The table below shows the number of accounts reviewed and the number of P800 forms issued for 2013-14 and 2014-15. Final figures for 2015-16 are not yet available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Accounts reviewed</p></td><td><p>P800 forms issued</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>45.86 million</p></td><td><p>5.43 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>45.81 million</p></td><td><p>5.04 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-23T15:57:13.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638614/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638614/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-18","Taxation: Forms","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many P800 adjustments were issued to individual taxpayers to correct for an over or under payment of income tax in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638615","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-28","<p>Electronic services and goods sold online to consumers in the UK are subject to UK VAT in the same way as if a consumer purchased them through other means.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-28T14:18:11.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638615/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638615/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-18","Taxation: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has undertaken or commissioned research on introducing an internet sales tax.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53703"
