"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638704","Department of Health","false","2016-11-23","<p>NHS employer organisations are responsible for the recruitment and retention of their staff and, therefore, individual National Health Service employers rather than the Department would assess the value of any such schemes they use in helping recruitment and retention.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-23T14:30:41.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638704/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638704/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","NHS: Company Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the value in recruiting and retaining staff of salary sacrifice company cars to employers in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","53726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638705","Department of Health","false","2016-11-23","<p>As locally led plans, it is vital that engagement with local government is driven by Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) themselves. We expect that different STPs will engage with local authorities in different ways, depending on what is appropriate for their area. The successful delivery of STPs will also require a close partnership between the National Health Service and local government.</p><p> </p><p>A number of STPs are led by local government leaders including Norfolk and Waveney; Nottinghamshire; Manchester; and, Birmingham and Solihull.</p><p> </p><p>National bodies, including NHS England and NHS Improvement, have also been working alongside the Local Government Association.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-23T14:52:03.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638705/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638705/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from local government leaders on sustainability and transformation plans.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","53717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638706","Department of Health","false","2016-11-28","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomes the progress that has already been made by Greater Manchester partners as they implement their ground-breaking devolution deal. The Department and other national partners continue to work with and support Greater Manchester as it realises its ambitious plans for transforming its health and social care system.</p><p> </p><p>Discussions with Greater Manchester are ongoing. However there are currently no plans to devolve responsibility and funding for community pharmacies, under the Cities and Local Devolution Act 2016, to the Greater Manchester Combined Authority.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-28T10:53:01.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638706/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638706/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","Pharmacy: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of changes to community pharmacy funding on the delivery of pharmaceutical services in Greater Manchester; and whether it is his intention to devolve (a) responsibility for and (b) funding of pharmacies to the Greater Manchester Combined Authority or its component local authorities.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638707","Department of Health","false","2016-11-28","<p>This is a matter for NHS England. Within its overall transformation resources NHS England has made an allocation of £450 million to Greater Manchester. Under the accountability arrangements established in its devolution agreement, the Greater Manchester Strategic Partnership Board will oversee the deployment of this funding to deliver the major change programme set out in its Health and Social Care Strategic Plan.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and other national partners will continue to work with and support the National Health Service in Greater Manchester as the plans for its health and social care system are realised.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomes the progress that has already been made.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-28T10:40:33.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638707/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638707/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","Health Services and Social Services: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the sufficiency of transitional/transformational funding for Greater Manchester health and social care devolution.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638708","Department of Health","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Department does not have a contract with Capita for moving medical records.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-23T16:10:42.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638708/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638708/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","Department of Health: Capita","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department's contract with Capita for moving medical records has cost to date.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","53828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638709","Home Office","false","2016-11-24","<p>The Immigration Enforcement Business Plan will be published in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-24T12:09:22.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638709/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638709/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-18","Immigration Enforcement Directorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to publish her Department's Immigration and Enforcement Business Plan 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","53856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638710","Home Office","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Home Office is responsible for the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 but does not itself have powers to freeze or recover assets. The powers in the Proceeds of Crime Act may be exercised by law enforcement agencies such as the National Crime Agency, Serious Fraud Office, constables and HM Revenue and Customs.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-11-23T17:10:47.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638710/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638710/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-18","Freezing of Assets: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from the alleged Klyuev organised crime group her Department has subjected to an (a) asset freeze and (b) asset recovery in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","53854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638711","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-28","<p>We want our prisons to be places where staff and prisoners alike feel safe and secure. The introduction of new ways of working to support prisoners to reform will achieve this while also increasing frontline staff numbers.</p><p> </p><p>Prison governors will be empowered to determine the precise grade mix and deployment of staff into their establishment to meet the individual needs of their specific prisoner population, in line with set minimum service requirements which are aligned to the NOMS Offender Management model. Staff numbers will vary across establishments, dependant on prisoner population and type of prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-28T17:53:24.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638711/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638711/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-18","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will provide a breakdown of the proposed additional 2,500 prison officers by prison.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638712","Home Office","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Violence Against Women and Girls Inter Ministerial Group met on 12 May and 13 October. Both meetings discussed cross-Government progress on the delivery of the Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-23T16:45:47.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638712/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638712/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-18","Violence against Women and Girls Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 17 November 2016 to Question 52462, on which dates the Inter-Ministerial Group on Violence against Women and Girls met in 2016.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","53769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638713","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-23","<p>Our HIV and AIDS work has focused on multilateral instruments (Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria, UNITAID and UNAIDS), given their greater reach and scale. The Global Fund helps countries avoid stock outs of drugs and supports patients to sustain treatment, which are two key factors in preventing drug resistance.</p><p>UNITAID has also played a key role in tackling HIV drug resistance by building the market for second-line antiretroviral treatment. Over 100,000 patients a year now have access to UNITAID-supported second-line HIV medicines.</p><p>We and our partners make use of reports such as the Global Report on Early Warning Indicators of HIV Drug Resistance published by WHO earlier this year.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-23T17:20:52.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638713/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638713/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 31 October 2016 to Question 50607, what assessment her Department has made of HIV drug resistance in the countries that her Department operates in; and what steps her Department is taking to tackle HIV drug resistance in those countries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","53776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638714","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-23","<p>The UK Government is playing a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries through on-grid and decentralised renewable energy. DFID has a range of programmes to increase investment.</p><p>For example, programmes in Kenya and Tanzania aim to stimulate investment in community scale, renewable energy mini-grids, increasing electricity access for millions of people, and our Renewable Energy and Adaptation to Climate Technologies challenge fund provides seed finance for renewable energy businesses. CDC, the UK’s Development Finance Institution, has committed US$330m of investment to renewable energy supporting five gigawatts of capacity generation.</p><p>Through the Energy Africa campaign the UK Government is also working with a range of African countries and businesses to accelerate the expansion of markets in Africa so that people can buy affordable solar energy systems.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-23T17:22:18.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638714/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638714/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2016 to Question 907183, what support the Government plans to give to improve investment in renewable energy to benefit people in developing countries; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","53738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638715","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-25","<p>The Leave No One Behind Promise means we will focus on the most vulnerable and disadvantaged, which includes groups affected by HIV and AIDS. The UK’s recent £1.1 billion pledge to the Global Fund to fight AIDs, TB and Malaria is a practical example of this commitment.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-25T12:48:52.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638715/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638715/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has for the inclusion of HIV and AIDS within its Leaving No-One Behind framework.","true","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","53739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638716","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-24","<p>DFID’s assessment of progress on the HIV response is drawn from reports and data produced by UNAIDS and other partners such as the World Health Organisation and the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria, along with reviews by DFID in-country health advisers.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-24T16:21:47.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638716/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638716/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has a methodology for ranking countries and regions on the adequacy of care and treatment that is available to fight HIV and AIDS in those countries and regions.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","53841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638717","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-24","<p>DFID Ministers regularly attend international summits and conferences where their presence can underline the UK’s high level commitments.</p><p>For example, the Minister of State, the Rt Hon The Lord Bates, will be opening the STOPAIDS World AIDS Day conference on 30 November 2016.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-24T16:30:18.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638717/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638717/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which international summits and conferences on tackling HIV and AIDS Ministers of her Department plan to attend in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","53842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638718","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-24","<p>The UK was the second largest international funder of HIV prevention, treatment and care between 2014 and 2015 and remains committed to helping end AIDS as a public health threat by 2030.</p><p>HIV funding was discussed with international counterparts as part of the dialogue on the recent Global Fund Replenishment. The UK Government supports calls for shared responsibility and global solidarity in the response to HIV to achieve the Global Goal target. We strongly believe countries should commit according to their ability to contribute.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-24T16:29:48.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638718/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638718/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her international counterparts on changes in the level of international donor funding for tackling HIV and AIDS between 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","53850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638719","Department of Health","false","2016-11-28","<p>Manchester Mental Health and Social Care Trust has provided healthcare in HMP Manchester since April 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Mental Health Inreach Team (MHIT) provides a specialist, comprehensive mental health service for prisoners at HMP Manchester.</p><p> </p><p>MHIT staff use the Care Programme Approach to mental health assessment and care planning when working with prisoners. This includes liaising with any family and carers, services outside the prison, including community mental health services in the prisoner's home location and the National Probation Service and Criminal Justice Liaison Team, to ensure that continuity of planning and care occurs as people move in and out of prison.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-28T15:09:38.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638719/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-18","Strangeways Prison: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make a statement on the adequacy of mental health assessments in HM Prison Strangeways, Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638720","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-28","<p>The information requested can be viewed in the Criminal Justice System outcomes by offence data tool on the Criminal Justice Systems Statistics Quarterly (December 2015) page on gov.uk.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-28T16:04:36.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638720/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638720/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-18","Young Offenders: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many fines have been issued by courts to children for criminal offences in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","53743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638721","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-06","<p>It is not usual practice for young people under the age of 18 to be re-categorised and transferred to the adult estate. In exceptional circumstances, a young person can be moved to the adult estate prior to reaching 18 years of age due to violent or disruptive behaviour which is putting other young people and/or staff at risk. Such moves are extremely rare and take place in line with an agreed approval process which requires sign-off by both the Chief Executive of the Youth Justice Board and the Deputy Director of Custody Young People’s Estate.</p><p>In the last year, one young person under the age of 18 was moved to a Young Offender Institution accommodating young adults aged 18 to 21.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-12-06T16:24:05.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638721/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638721/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-18","Young Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times children under the age of 18 have been re-categorised and transferred to adult prisons in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","53744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638722","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-28","<p>The safety of both young people and staff in youth custody is of utmost importance. We are currently developing a strategy which aims to improve safety across the youth estate, including at Medway, Oakhill and Rainsbrook.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-28T17:37:27.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638722/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638722/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-18","Secure Training Centres: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what her Department's current assessment of the level of safety is for staff at (a) Medway, (b) Oakhill and (c) Rainsbrook secure training centres.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","53741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638723","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-28","<p>The prison population by establishment and the number of prison officers (Band 3 – 5) for each public sector prison in England and Wales are published on gov.uk.</p><p>As data are only published on staffing levels from June 2013, the attached spreadsheet provides staffing data as at March of each year for the period 2006 to 2013. Ratios can be calculated from these published figures.</p><p>We are committed to transforming prisons into places of safety and reform and we’ve announced a major overhaul of the prison system including 2,500 extra frontline officers.</p><p>As an immediate action we have already invested £14 million to provide more than 400 extra staff in ten of the most challenging prisons. <br> <br> We are also introducing a new scheme to attract top graduates and former servicemen and women into the service, and giving governors greater flexibility over recruitment so they can address staffing quickly.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-28T17:55:54.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638723/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638723/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-18","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the ratio of prisoners to prison officers was in each prison in England in each year from 2006.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638724","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-11-28","<p>The issues relating to Lough Foyle date back to a 1662 charter of Charles II, which granted the waters and bed (as well as the fisheries) of Lough Foyle to the Irish Society, and included them as part of County Londonderry.</p><p> </p><p>In practice, the regulation of activities in the Lough is now the responsibility of the Loughs Agency, a cross-border body established under the Belfast Agreement of 1998.</p><p> </p><p>We remain fully committed to these arrangements and continue to work closely with the Irish Government over improvements to the management of the Lough. Like the Irish Government, we do not anticipate these issues forming part of the negotiations over the UK’s exit from the European Union.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-11-28T11:44:43.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638724/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638724/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-18","County Londonderry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2016 to Question 52620, on County Londonderry, what the legal basis is for the Government's position given in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","53768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638725","Prime Minister","false","2016-11-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave, on 16 November, to the hon. Member for West Dunbarton- shire (Mr Docherty-Hughes), Official Report, column 237, the hon. Member for Ynys Môn (Mr Owen), Official Report, column 240, the right hon. Member for Islington North (Mr Corbyn), Official Report, column 229, the right hon. Member for Moray (Mr Robertson), Official Report, column 232 and the hon. Member for North East Fife (Mr Gethins), Official Report, column 236.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-11-23T12:17:09.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638725/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638725/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-11-18","Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what discussions she has had with the (a) Scottish Government, (b) Welsh Government and (c) Northern Ireland Executive on the (i) European Social Funds, (ii) European Regional Development Fund and (iii) access and membership of the single market.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","53831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638726","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>High Speed 2 Limited estimate that around a total of 25,000 private sector employment opportunities will be generated in the process of building the HS2 railway, with a further 3,000 jobs to operate it once finished. The London-West Midlands Environmental Statement (Volume 3, Route-Wide Effects, November 2013) estimated that the equivalent of 14,600 full time employment opportunities would be generated in the construction of Phase One. The government has not made an estimate of the number of construction jobs created through each construction contract in each year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T13:51:19.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638726/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638726/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of construction jobs that are likely to be created through each construction contract as part of High Speed 2 Phase One in each year.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","53798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638727","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The steps taken to promote the recruitment of local workers (as well as disadvantaged and under-represented groups) are set out at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509181/G4_-_Approaches_to_Training_and_Employment_v1.4.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509181/G4_-_Approaches_to_Training_and_Employment_v1.4.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Measures to help small and medium sized enterprises (SMEs) and local businesses from across the UK access supply chain opportunities are also included in the major works contracts. HS2 Ltd require every procurement to be fair, transparent and competitive and to maximise the opportunities for SMEs to provide the works.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T14:07:56.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638727/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638727/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to promote the recruitment of local workers for the construction and operation of High Speed 2 (HS2) in (a) London, (b) Birmingham and (c) the rest of the HS2 Phase One route; and what reporting requirements he is placing on HS2 contractors with regard to (i) local labour recruitment, (ii) spending with local suppliers and (iii) recruitment from disadvantaged and under-represented groups.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","53814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638728","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-28","<p>Highways England only holds data for vehicles using the Dartford Crossing (during the charging hours of 06.00 hrs to 22.00 hrs) from April 2010 to October 2016. There is no data available prior to April 2010.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The total number of cars and HGVs for this period is shown in the following tables:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Where data for the full year is available: </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>2011-2015</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Northbound and Southbound*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Cars</p></td><td><p>30,438,135</p></td><td><p>29,658,825</p></td><td><p>28,942,518</p></td><td><p>29,222,669</p></td><td><p>31,168,494</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of HGV’s**</p></td><td><p>4,863,481</p></td><td><p>4,850,745</p></td><td><p>4,867,198</p></td><td><p>5,010,762</p></td><td><p>5,395,963</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Crossings</p></td><td><p>44,694,780</p></td><td><p>43,851,122</p></td><td><p>43,267,156</p></td><td><p>44,366,500</p></td><td><p>46,660,250</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Where data for part of the year is available:</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>2010: Data for 9 months: April to December 2010 only</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Northbound and Southbound* </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Cars</p></td><td><p>23,659,574</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of HGV’s*</p></td><td><p>3,611,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Crossings</p></td><td><p>34,265,357</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>2016: Data for 10 months: January to October 2016 only</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Northbound and Southbound* </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Cars</p></td><td><p>26,681,951</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of HGV’s**</p></td><td><p>4,763,703</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Crossings</p></td><td><p>40,316,552</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>*crossings combined</p><p>**Multi-axle Goods Vehicles</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-28T13:51:25.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638728/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638728/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the change in the number of (a) cars and (b) HGVs using the Dartford Crossing in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","53838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638729","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The information is not held centrally for the breakdowns requested and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","53845 ; 53846 ; 53847 ; 53848 ; 53849","2016-11-24T14:31:26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638729/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638729/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","M25: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average speed was on vehicles travelling between junction 2 and junction 31 of the M25 on weekday evenings between 4pm and 7pm in August (a) 2008, (b) 2012 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","53837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638730","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The steps taken to promote the recruitment of local workers (as well as disadvantaged and under-represented groups) are set out at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509181/G4_-_Approaches_to_Training_and_Employment_v1.4.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509181/G4_-_Approaches_to_Training_and_Employment_v1.4.pdf</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T14:03:21.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638730/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638730/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what definition will be used for the term local workers in relation to recruitment policies introduced for the construction phase of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","53813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638731","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-28","<p>The Dartford Crossing consists of two northbound tunnels and the southbound Queen Elizabeth II Bridge. In the last 12 month period there were a total of 14 occasions when the crossing was fully closed either northbound or southbound.</p><p> </p><p>There were six bridge closures (four due to high winds, one due to a police led incident and one due to a suicide), four tunnel closures (one due to problems with the Traffic Safety System, one due to problems with the reporting tool for fire safety and two due to car fires) and four closures of the carriageway leading up to the crossing due to police led incidents.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-28T13:36:30.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638731/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638731/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions in the last 12 months the Dartford Crossing has been closed; and what the cause was of each such closure.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","53804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638732","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>HS2 Ltd remain committed to a target date of December 2026 for the introduction of services for Phase One of the project.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T13:47:25.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638732/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638732/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the chart entitled HS2 Review Phase 1 Target Schedule on page 10 of the High Speed 2 Plus supporting slides, published by HS2 Limited on 17 March 2014, if he will update that chart so that it provides the latest contribution schedule for High Speed 2 Phase One.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","53773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638733","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The Dartcharge Post Opening Project Evaluation (POPE) report, which will include an assessment of air quality, will be completed in Spring 2017.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-24T11:55:11.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638733/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638733/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33141, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of the removal of the tollbooths at the Dartford Crossing on air quality in Dartford.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","53774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638734","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>Working with the Department for Communities and Local Government, my Department has regular discussions with Local Authorities to support the development of their local growth strategies. These strategies set out their plans to catalyse the growth and regeneration benefits of HS2 in their area and can include details on how the benefits of HS2 will be aligned with the local transport plan ambitions.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T11:47:13.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638734/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638734/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with local authorities to encourage coordination between local transport plans and High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","53793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638735","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>High Speed 2 Limited estimate that HS2 will support up to 100,000 jobs around HS2 stations. The western leg of Phase 2b is estimated to support 30,000 to 43,600 of these jobs. The government has not made an estimate of jobs created in Cheshire. Other organisations have produced their own estimates and ambitions for jobs supported by HS2. For example, the Northern Gateway Development Zone in Cheshire and Staffordshire have plans to help create 120,000 new jobs by 2040. They are currently preparing an HS2 Growth Strategy on how HS2 will contribute to supporting this number of new jobs in the area.</p><p> </p><p>High Speed 2 Limited also estimate that around 25,000 private sector employment opportunities are expected to be generated in the process of building the HS2 railway, with a further 3,000 jobs to operate it once finished.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-24T11:50:19.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638735/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638735/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs that will be created in (a) Cheshire and (b) the North West as a result of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","53794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638736","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>When approached by a train operator, the Secretary of State has the power to grant exemptions under section 183 of the Equality Act 2010 for areas of minor non-compliance, which cannot be rectified for technical or operational reasons, that are identified by the operator. All applications for exemption are subject to stakeholder and public consultation, including scrutiny from the Disabled Person’s Transport Advisory Committee, the Office of Rail and Road, Transport Focus and (if applicable) London TravelWatch. The Secretary of State has a duty to publish an annual report to parliament on all exemptions he grants.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-23T15:50:27.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638736/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638736/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Railways: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has received reports of any train operating companies that are not compliant with the Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","53786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638737","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>The operator bears the legal responsibility for ensuring that the vehicles it operates are compliant with Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010 if those Regulations apply to its operations. The Office of Rail and Road is the enforcing body for the Regulations.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-23T15:54:10.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638737/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638737/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Railways: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which body is responsible for ensuring that train operating companies are compliant with the that Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","53787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638738","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Tolls are set by the Severn Bridges Act 1992. The prices that will apply will be confirmed shortly.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-23T15:57:54.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638738/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638738/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, at what level tolls at the Severn Bridge will be set from January 2017.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","53757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638739","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Being able to analyse the impact of our policies on particular groups is a fundamental part of good policy-making which the Department undertakes. However, collating information on all the policies and guidance which the Department has developed or issued which have been subject to an equality impact assessment since 2010, could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-23T15:45:56.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638739/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638739/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Department for Transport: Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will detail all policies or guidance which his Department has developed or issued which have been subject to an equality impact assessment since 2010; and what the outcome of those assessments was.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","53753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638740","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Compliance with the standards of the Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010 (RVAR) is a mandatory duty placed on an operator. Operators are required to maintain a safety management system that has been accepted by the Office of Rail and Road, and this includes procedures for ensuring that new vehicles comply with statutory requirements. For older vehicles, the Regulations contain a compliance deadline of 1 January 2020. The Department is working closely with owners and operators of older rolling stock to which RVAR applies to ensure that the deadline in met.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-23T15:42:07.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638740/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Railways: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of which train operating companies are fully compliant with the Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","53752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638741","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The Department is not currently undertaking market research on the number of incidents relating to truck and bus wheel loss. The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency continues to investigate reports of safety-related vehicle defects and its examiners also carry out large numbers of vehicle safety inspections.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-24T12:13:11.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638741/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638741/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department is undertaking market research to improve its estimates on the number of incidents relating to truck and bus wheel loss.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","53691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638742","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-24","<p>The estimated completion date for the M3 junction 2-4a smart motorway scheme, which is currently in construction, is June 2017. Work on the further M3 smart motorway scheme between Junctions 9-14 is expected to start in 2019/20 and complete by 2021/22. Both are in line with Highways England’s delivery plan and are currently on target.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-24T14:20:24.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638742/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638742/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-18","M3","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the level of progress of the work to upgrade the M3 motorway.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","53696"
