ns have been made by (1) HMRC and (2) DWP pursuant to Article 7 of Regulation (EC) No 987/2009 since 1 May 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638259","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>Regulation (EC) 883/2004 co-ordinates social security systems across the EU, EEA and Switzerland. Regulation (EC) No 987/2009 is the implementation regulation which provides for administrative co-operation between Member States to implement the co-ordination regulation.</p><p> </p><p>Article 6 provides for a Member State to make benefit payments on a provisional basis as the Member State of residence if there is a dispute with another Member State as to who is responsible for the payment of benefits. Article 7 provides for a Member State to make a provisional award of benefit if another Member State has not provided all the evidence requested from them.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not collect information on the number of provisional benefit payments made on the basis of either Article 6 or 7 of Regulation (EC) No 987/2009.</p><p> </p><p>There is published guidance on how to determine an award of benefit through the application of Article 6 (Annex A DWP Annex B HMRC). This is part of the Decision Makers Guidance which is made available to the public.</p><p> </p><p>In domestic guidance there is the facility for a decision maker to make an award of benefit where the evidence required is incomplete, with a revision of that award undertaken, if appropriate, once the required evidence is received. This would cover claims made under Article 7. Each claim to benefit is assessed on a case by case basis.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL3327 ; HL3328","2016-12-01T16:30:05.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638259/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638259/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-17","Social Security Benefits: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guidance HMRC and DWP have (1) published, or (2) issued to their staff, about the application of the provisions of Articles 6 and 7 of Regulation (EC) No 987/2009 concerning provisional benefit payments and calculations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638260","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-28","<p>In October 2016 the Office for Low Emission Vehicles announced a £2.5m grant scheme to support the installation of chargepoints on public streets in residential areas where motorists do not have off-street parking. Applications will open to local authorities in the coming weeks.</p><p> </p><p>This scheme will complement the existing Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme, which gives eligible plug-in vehicle drivers up to £500 off the costs of installation of a dedicated domestic chargepoint in a driveway or garage. This grant is available to electric vehicle owners who live in flats, as long as there is dedicated parking space.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-28T12:08:34.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638260/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638260/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-17","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 17 November (HL 3036), what measures they plan to take to encourage the provision of public charge points for electric vehicles in residential areas where there is a predominance of flats or terraced houses and parking provision is confined to public roads.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL3330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638261","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Supported Accommodation Review was published online on 21 November and can be accessed on the gov.uk website.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-12-01T16:18:30.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638261/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638261/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-17","Supported Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Statement by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions (HCWS154), when they intend to publish their evidence review of the scale, scope and cost of the supported housing sector.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL3331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638262","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We take the welfare of persons detained under immigration powers very seriously and no form of ill-treatment or discrimination is tolerated.</p><p>Published guidance for staff in the immigration detention estate, Detention Services Order 2/2016 ‘Lesbian, gay and bisexual detainees in the detention estate’ and Detention Services Order 11/2012 'Care &amp; Management of Transsexual Detainees' sets out how detainees with these protected characteristics should be safeguarded and treated in detention.</p><p>The Government is currently considering the report ‘No Safe Refuge: Experiences of LGBT asylum seekers in detention’ by the UK Lesbian and Gay Immigration Group and Stonewall.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3333","2016-12-01T11:30:33.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638262/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638262/answer","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detainees_v2_1_external.pdf ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees.pdf","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detainees_v2_1_external.pdf ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees.pdf","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detai ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detai ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638262/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the report by the UK Lesbian and Gay Immigration Group and Stonewall, <i>No Safe Refuge</i>: <i>the experiences of LGBT asylum seekers in immigration detention centres</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638263","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We take the welfare of persons detained under immigration powers very seriously and no form of ill-treatment or discrimination is tolerated.</p><p>Published guidance for staff in the immigration detention estate, Detention Services Order 2/2016 ‘Lesbian, gay and bisexual detainees in the detention estate’ and Detention Services Order 11/2012 'Care &amp; Management of Transsexual Detainees' sets out how detainees with these protected characteristics should be safeguarded and treated in detention.</p><p>The Government is currently considering the report ‘No Safe Refuge: Experiences of LGBT asylum seekers in detention’ by the UK Lesbian and Gay Immigration Group and Stonewall.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3332","2016-12-01T11:30:33.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638263/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638263/answer","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detainees_v2_1_external.pdf ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees.pdf","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detainees_v2_1_external.pdf ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees.pdf","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detai ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees","11_2012_-_Care_and_Management_of_transsexual_detai ; Lesbian_Gay_Bisexual_Detainees","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638263/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to address the concerns of harassment of LGBT asylum seekers raised in the report by the UK Lesbian and Gay Immigration Group and Stonewall <i>No Safe Refuge</i>, and the concerns raised by the inquiry into the use of immigration detention by the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Refugees and All-Party Parliamentary Group on Migration.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638264","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>The guidance in respect of the Government’s policy on adults at risk in immigration detention came into force on 12 September 2016. The Government has no immediate plans to revise it.</p><p>There is a general presumption of liberty for all individuals. Detention is used only when necessary, most often in order to enforce an individual’s removal from the UK. The adults at risk policy makes particular provision for individuals who are regarded as vulnerable, by reference to a list of vulnerability “indicators”.</p><p>Transsexual (and intersex) individuals are included in the list of indicators, following a recommendation from Stephen Shaw, in the report of his review into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons, that transsexual people should be presumed unsuitable for detention. Furthermore, any LGB individual who exhibits any of the indicators, or who is otherwise recognised as vulnerable, would fall within the scope of the policy.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-01T11:31:44.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638264/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638264/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to revise the Immigration Act 2016 guidance on adults at risk in immigration detention; and if so, whether they will include a presumption that LGBT immigrants, particularly those seeking asylum, should not be detained.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638265","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>The number of people who have been resettled under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme is published in the quarterly Home Office statistics. The sexuality and gender identity of those vulnerable people being resettled under this scheme is not routinely recorded or reported.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-01T11:32:06.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638265/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638265/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many LGBT Syrian refugees have been resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Person Resettlement programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638266","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We are clear that our scheme will prioritise the most vulnerable refugees, and that is why under the VPR scheme the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) identifies refugees for resettlement using its established vulnerability criteria.</p><p>We are working with UNHCR and other partners to intensify their outreach to groups that might otherwise be reluctant to register for fear of stigma/discrimination and unaware of the safe space and options available to them. This includes all religious minorities, LGBT people, people with disabilities, survivors of torture and sexual violence and others.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-01T15:59:42.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638266/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638266/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps have been taken to assist LGBT Syrian refugees to access the Syrian Vulnerable Person Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638267","Home Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>Refugees being resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Person’s Resettlement scheme are invited to attend cultural orientation before they arrive in the UK.</p><p>This includes information on the diverse and inclusive nature of UK society and on the rights and responsibilities of citizens and those resident here. Once in the UK they are provided with a 12 month support package tailored to their individual needs. This includes accommodation, caseworker support and integration assistance, medical and social care needs and English language tuition. We ask local authorities to think carefully about whether they have the infrastructure and support networks needed to ensure the appropriate care and integration of these refugees before they begin resettling people.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-01T15:57:50.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638267/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638267/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps have been taken to assist LGBT Syrian refugees who have been identified by the UNHCR as eligible for resettlement in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Person Resettlement Scheme (1) before, and (2) following, their arrival in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638268","Department of Health","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England. All providers of regulated activities must register with the CQC and follow a set of fundamental standards of safety and quality.</p><p> </p><p>The fundamental standards describe the basic requirements that care providers, including care homes, should always meet, and set out the outcomes that services users should always expect.</p><p> </p><p>The standards include requirements regarding the facilities and equipment care homes must have. One refers to premises and equipment, and requires that the provider must ensure that all premises and equipment are clean, secure, suitable for the purpose used, properly maintained and appropriately located for the purpose for which they are used.</p><p> </p><p>A further standard refers to safe care and treatment and includes a requirement that equipment used by the provider is safe, used in a safe way and that sufficient quantities are available to ensure the safety of service users and to meet their needs.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC inspects against the standards and has a range of enforcement powers that it can employ if it finds a provider is not following them.</p><p> </p><p>Following inspection, the CQC rates providers on a four point scale - outstanding, good, requires improvement and inadequate. These ratings give patients and the public a fair, balanced and easy to understand assessment of performance and quality. Services rated inadequate receive help to improve, but any that are unable or unwilling to do so face closure.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-23T16:13:04.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638268/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638268/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-17","Care Homes: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that care homes have sufficient facilities to function adequately.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638269","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government is committed to the growth of the construction industry; and announced at the Autumn Statement a new National Productivity Investment Fund, of which £7.2 billion is to be used to support the construction of new homes and £1.3 billion will be invested in roads and local transport.</p><p>Additionally, £2.3 billion will be invested in a new Housing Infrastructure Fund, of which £1.4 billion will be used to build 40,000 new affordable homes, including some for shared ownership and some for affordable rent.</p><p>The Government has shown that it is committed to infrastructure development: earlier this month my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Transport reiterated this Government’s commitment to HS2; in October we announced support for a new runway at Heathrow; and in September we reaffirmed our commitment to Hinkley Point C.</p><p>The Government is working closely with the Construction Leadership Council to ensure that UK businesses can make the most of these and other opportunities.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-11-29T15:01:40.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638269/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638269/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-17","Construction: Industry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures they are taking to encourage the growth of the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638270","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-01","<p>The government remains committed to returning the public finances to balance, and has set out a new fiscal objective to achieve this at the earliest possible date in the next Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The government’s new fiscal mandate for this Parliament is to reduce the cyclically-adjusted deficit to less than 2% of GDP by 2020-21. The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) forecast that this rule will be met 2 years early with £26.6bn of headroom.</p><p> </p><p>The OBR also forecast that the headline deficit will be reduced to 0.7% of GDP in 2021-22, the smallest deficit in two decades. The current balance, which is defined as the headline deficit excluding investment spending, returns to surplus in 2019-20.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-01T15:34:50.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638270/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638270/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Public Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they intend to take to reduce the current budget deficit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638271","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-01","<p>As we conduct our negotiations, it must be a priority to regain more control of the numbers of people who come here from Europe. We are considering very carefully the options that are open to us. As part of that it is important that we understand the impacts on the different sectors of the economy and the labour market from any changes that we make. My Department, working with officials across government, continues to undertake a wide range of data analyses to inform the UK's position.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-01T15:23:23.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638271/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638271/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-17","Labour Market","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect of Brexit on the labour market.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638272","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p>Immigrants who have come to the UK to work have brought significant benefits to Britain – we are a tolerant, welcoming nation encouraging the brightest and best to come to our shores. That will always be the case.</p><p>But it’s clear that there is no consent in Britain for uncontrolled migration from Europe.</p><p>It is important to note that those who hold British Citizenship can also be classed as non UK born.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-11-29T17:04:28.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638272/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638272/answer","Lord Taylor PQ HL3342 FINAL (1) (2) (1).pdf","Lord Taylor PQ HL3342 FINAL (1) (2) (1).pdf","UKSA Response to HL3342","UKSA Response to HL3342","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638272/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-17","Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of figures published by the Office for National Statistics which show that, in the past year, around 95 per cent of new workers were born outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638273","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-24","<p>A comprehensive Review of the Monetary Policy Framework was published in 2013, considering the benefits and costs of a number of different monetary policy frameworks. The review concluded that operational independence has helped improve credibility and accountability of monetary policy, leading to stable inflation and inflation expectations, and in turn macroeconomic stability.</p><p> </p><p>The current remit for the Monetary Policy Committee reflects the assessment set out in the 2013 Review, which reaffirms the Bank of England’s operation independence and a flexible inflation targeting framework.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-24T17:30:06.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638273/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638273/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Bank of England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which the Bank of England should be independent of the Government.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL3343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638274","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>We have not raised this specific issue. The UK continues to press for an end to restrictions and urgent measures to relieve the humanitarian suffering of those in Gaza.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-29T15:36:06.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638274/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638274/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-17","Gaza: Prosthetics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel to expedite the passage of materials for prosthetic limbs through Erez Crossing for patients at the Artificial Limb and Polio Centre in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638275","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 and ensure a functioning statute book on the day we leave the EU. This ‘Great Repeal Bill’ will end the authority of EU law and return power to the UK. The Bill will convert existing European Union law into domestic law, wherever practical and in that context all relevant legislation is currently being identified and assessed.</p><p>The Government will set out the content of the Bill and its implications in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-29T14:57:01.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638275/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638275/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will list the statutory instruments currently in force which were made under section 2(2) of the European Communities Act 1972, the subject matter of which falls within the departmental responsibilities of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Tankerness",,"Lord Wallace of Tankerness","HL3345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638276","Attorney General","false","2016-11-25","<p>The Attorney General’s Office, Government Legal Department and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate report quarterly sickness absence statistics to Cabinet Office and define mental disorders as absences for reasons of stress; mood affective disorders; disorders of personality &amp; behaviour and schizophrenia.</p><p> </p><p>Based on these definitions, the number of working days lost due to mental disorders in these three departments in each of the last three financial years is as follows:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Year Days lost to Mental Disorders</strong></p><p><strong> AGO GLD HMCPSI</strong></p><p>01/04/2013 – 31/03/2014 23 1,843 15</p><p>01/04/2014 – 31/03/2015 0 1,704.5 168</p><p>01/04/2015 – 31/03/2016 0 1,551 28</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the last 3 financial years the following numbers of absence days have been recorded by the Serious Fraud Office for reasons of Anxiety, Depressive Disorder or Mental Disorder:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Year Days lost to Mental Disorders</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2013/14 18 days</p><p>2014/15 176.5 days</p><p>2015/16 507 days</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this the following number of absence days have been recorded as Stress or Work Related Stress:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Year Days lost to Mental Disorders</strong></p><p> </p><p>2013/14 105 days</p><p>2014/15 195 days</p><p>2015/16 529 days</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The number of working days lost to mental illness in the Crown Prosecution Service for the last three financial years is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Number of working days lost due to Mental Illness, including stress.</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of working days lost which were attributed to stress. </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2013-31/03/2014</p></td><td><p>16028</p></td><td><p>7844</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2014-31/03/2015</p></td><td><p>15989</p></td><td><p>7807</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2015-31/03/2016</p></td><td><p>11854</p></td><td><p>5856</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The absence reasons which are included in the Mental Illness category are categorised in line with World Health Organisation (WHO).</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-11-25T16:04:45.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638276/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638276/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-11-17","Attorney General: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in the Law Officers' Departments in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638277","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-24","<p>In line with other Government Departments, the Department for Exiting the European Union will pay its legal costs from its budget. As the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union said in his statement to the House on 7 November 2016, all those figures will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-11-24T16:58:43.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638277/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638277/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-17","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the potential cost to the public purse of the Government's appeal to the Supreme Court on triggering Article 50.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638278","Attorney General","false","2016-11-25","<p>In 2015-16, the Government Legal Department employed the full time equivalent of 175 agency and contracted staff at a cost of £9,231,000.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-11-25T09:32:48.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638278/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638278/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-11-17","Attorney General: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many agency staff the Government Legal Department employed at what cost in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","53587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638279","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Kids Company was required to meet a clear set of delivery targets. These were regularly monitored and reviewed to ensure Kids Company were delivering the outcomes set out in the Grant Agreement.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-23T13:55:17.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638279/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638279/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what value for money assessment the Government made of the first payment to Kids Company of 2015-16 made in accordance with Section 70 of the Charities Act 2001.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638280","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-24","<p>The table below sets out information about working days lost in my Department due to sickness absence related to mental illness over the last three calendar years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Working Days Lost due to Mental Illness</p></td><td><p>1574</p></td><td><p>1382</p></td><td><p>1443</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>As % of All Sick Absence</p></td><td><p>39%</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td><td><p>29%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>As % of Total Workforce</p></td><td><p>1.7%</p></td><td><p>1.6%</p></td><td><p>1.7%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Cabinet Office is committed to reducing work related absence due to mental illness and has a number of services in place to support members of staff suffering from such conditions. Our Workwell community is staffed by volunteers who aim to make Cabinet Office a happy and healthy workplace through a number of interventions including a listening service for staff. We also offer a 24 hour counselling support helpline through our Employee Assistance Programme provider and advocate early referral to our occupational health service where appropriate for advice on a number of conditions including mental health.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-11-24T12:04:42.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638280/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638280/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-17","Cabinet Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638281","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-22","<p>We are still engaging with the Official Receiver about retrieval of any remaining Grant funds.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-22T16:33:32.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638281/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638281/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much of the first grant the Government paid to Kids Company in 2015-16 is her Department seeking to recover for the public purse.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638282","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Kids Company was required to meet a clear set of delivery targets. An independent third party was appointed by Cabinet Office to independently monitor and evaluate the grant and outcomes Kids Company were reporting.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-23T13:27:17.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638282/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638282/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the amount of money paid to Kids Company in 2015-16 that went towards fulfilling that charity's objectives.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638283","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Grant agreement set out a clear set of delivery targets which Kids Company were expected to achieve.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-22T16:31:41.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638283/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638283/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government made any provisions for the purposes for which the first assistance funds paid to Kids Company in 2015-16 could be used.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638284","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-22","<p>We treat Cyber Security extremely seriously. Our 2015 National Security Strategy confirmed that cyber remains a top threat to the UK’s economic and national security. The threat posed by cyber-attacks continues to grow in both scale and complexity. Cyber security is crucial for keeping the UK safe.</p><p>To meet the challenges of cyber security threats, the government launched its new National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-2021 on the 1 November. Supported by £1.9billion of transformational investment, the strategy sets out ambitious policies and capabilities to protect the UK in cyber space.</p><p>The strategy is available online here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-cyber-security-strategy-" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-cyber- security-strategy-</a> 2016-to-2021.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-11-22T12:05:37.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638284/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638284/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-17","Cybercrime: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government has made an assessment of the level of potential risk of cyber interference by foreign governments in elections in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","53501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638285","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-24","<p>The information requested is not available. HM Revenue and Customs does not collect data on VAT and Customs Duty from traders to this level of detail.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-24T17:33:37.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638285/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638285/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Taxation: Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the revenue accrued by HM Treasury through tax on ivory artworks and objets d'art in each of the last five years; and if his Department will make an estimate of the potential cost to the public purse of a ban on the ivory trade in the UK in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","53507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638286","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-24","<p>The Government announced at Budget 2016 a £6.7 billion business rates reduction package benefitting all ratepayers, and recommitted to this at Autumn Statement 2016. This package includes permanently doubling and increasing the thresholds of Small Business Rate Relief from April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>These reforms mean businesses, including those in London, with a property with a rateable value of £12,000 and below will receive 100% relief. Businesses with a property with a rateable value between £12,000 and £15,000 will receive tapered relief.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-24T17:34:39.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638286/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638286/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Non-domestic Rates: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of increasing Small Business Rate Relief for businesses in London.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","53490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638287","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-24","<p>HM Treasury and HM Revenue and Customs do not hold information on pension entitlements administered by other EU countries. Whilst taxpayers need to report such payments, reporting is combined with certain other forms of foreign income, notably payments from foreign private pensions.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-24T17:32:59.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638287/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638287/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","State Retirement Pensions: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information (a) his Department and (b) HM Revenue and Customs holds on the number of UK pensioners who receive state pensions from other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","53492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638288","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Government has set out its objective for a comprehensive and effective model of public country-by-country reporting that is agreed on a multilateral basis. The UK will remain supportive of international efforts – in the EU and elsewhere in the world - to deliver that objective.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-22T15:28:00.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638288/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638288/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Company Accounts: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to participate in EU proposals to introduce a form of public country-by-country reporting after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","53534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638289","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-22T15:15:36.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638289/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638289/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings he, his predecessor or Ministers of his Department have had during 2016 to date with representatives of multinational enterprises which have a UK turnover exceeding £600 million annually.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","53532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638290","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Government has set out its objective for a comprehensive and effective model of public country-by-country reporting that is agreed on a multilateral basis.</p><p>That means getting sufficient international agreement such that all groups – both UK headquartered and non-UK headquartered – are required to report accessible information for a broad range of countries in which they operate.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","53619","2016-11-22T15:37:21.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638290/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638290/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Company Accounts: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44206, what his policy is on which countries would need to introduce public country-by-country reporting before the UK would introduce such reporting.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","53597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638291","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The operation of monetary policy in the UK is independent of Government. This is a crucial cornerstone of the UK’s macroeconomic framework. The Government’s position on this has not changed.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-22T15:18:53.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638291/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638291/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Bank of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it remains government policy to maintain the Bank of England's independence.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","53670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638292","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>We have always been clear that this is a new chapter for the United Kingdom, but our economy is fundamentally strong. We will work closely with the Scottish Government – and get the best possible deal for all parts of our United Kingdom as we conduct our negotiations for leaving the EU.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-22T15:31:27.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638292/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638292/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Public Expenditure: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on Scotland's public finances.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","53685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638293","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force, until exit negotiations have concluded. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p>The Government expects to lay the implementing legislation to transpose the revised Payment Services Directive (PSDII) in Parliament in early 2017 and will be consulting on the draft legislation shortly.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-22T15:24:40.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638293/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638293/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Payments: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) the timetable for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive and (b) date on which regulations arising from that Directive will be laid before Parliament.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","53663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638294","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not collect the information requested.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-22T15:28:43.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638294/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638294/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","PAYE","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of employers' PAYE payments to HM Revenue and Customs could not be reconciled correctly to the employer's PAYE account for the PAYE period in which they arose in each month since real time information was introduced.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638295","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has annual data of the number of employers who have disputed their liability to PAYE.</p><p>In 2014-15, of the 1.8 million employer schemes, 37,065 formally disputed their liability to PAYE. In 2015-16, of the 2 million employer schemes, the number of employers formally disputing their liability was 40,902.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-22T15:30:14.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638295/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638295/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","PAYE","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employers have formally disputed HM Revenue and Customs' calculation of their liability to PAYE in each month since real-time information began.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638296","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Government has set out its objective for a comprehensive and effective model of public country-by-country reporting that is agreed on a multilateral basis.</p><p>That means getting sufficient international agreement such that all groups – both UK headquartered and non-UK headquartered – are required to report accessible information for a broad range of countries in which they operate.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","53597","2016-11-22T15:37:21.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638296/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638296/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Company Accounts: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44206, how many countries would be deemed sufficient to trigger the UK's introduction of public country-by-country reporting.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","53619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638297","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-22","<p>The independent Office for National Statistics is responsible for producing the calculation of the Consumer Price Index measure of inflation. The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) is responsible for producing independent economic and fiscal forecasts. The OBR will publish a full analysis of the prospects for inflation in their forecast at Autumn Statement.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-22T15:21:00.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638297/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638297/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-17","Inflation: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the change in the value of Sterling on the cost of food in the calculation of inflation for UK households.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","53646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638298","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Department distributes funding to local government through the Local Government Finance Settlement. In addition local government raises its own finance through local taxes. Social care funding is not ring-fenced and local government already has autonomy to determine how best to manage its own finances to ensure it delivers the appropriate level of services for its residents.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-22T11:50:09.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638298/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638298/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-17","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to give local authorities full financial autonomy for social care funding.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","53638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638299","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government is carefully considering the findings of the Ollerenshaw Review and will respond in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-29T19:31:46.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638299/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638299/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-17","Local Council Tax Support Schemes Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to respond to the findings of the Ollerenshaw Review of Local Council Tax Support.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","53593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638300","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-01","<p>This Government is committed to delivering the Northern Powerhouse; it remains central to our plans to build an economy that works for all. This is why in previous rounds of Local Growth Deals we have invested £2.8 billion in Northern Powerhouse regions. This includes £863.8 million for the Local Enterprise Partnerships that cover Hull and Selby as follows: £113.6 million for the Humber, £122.2 million for York, North Yorkshire and East Riding, and £628 million for Leeds City Region.</p><p>The train operators that serve Hull are planning to deliver a range of benefits for passengers: new rolling stock, faster journey times, and improvements to Hull station.</p><p>Due to bi-modal trains that will be built in the North East, these benefits can be delivered without the need for electrification. This will mean better journeys for passengers without having to wait for an electrified route and will avoid the inconvenience this would cause. A direct service to Hull on the Trans Pennine Express Network will remain in place.</p><p>The Arriva Rail North franchise, which started in April, has committed to upgrading the Hull-Doncaster-Sheffield route to a new high-quality ‘Northern Connect’ service. There will be new or refurbished trains on these longer-distance services, with faster journeys and stations staffed daily, with catering services and free Wi-Fi at each one.</p><p>Passengers travelling to Hull and to East Riding will benefit from other improvement including Virgin Trains East Coast running faster services when their new fleet of Azuma trains are introduced in 2018, taking up to 6-7 minutes off the route from London to Hull.</p><p>First Hull Trains recently announced a £60 million investment in five new AT300 bid-mode trains of five carriages each. These will take advantage of the existing electrified East Coast line and then continue on to Hull via Selby.</p><p>We are determined to strengthen transport links across Northern towns and cities, so that people have greater choice and flexibility over the places they choose to work and live.</p><p>We have created Transport for the North (TfN) to develop transport plans that drive economic growth. We have committed £50 million over this parliament and are working to put the organisation on a statutory footing, so that TfN can effectively deliver its objectives.</p><p>We are also investing £13 billion in transport in the North during this parliament, to take forward key projects in the Northern Powerhouse.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-12-01T16:45:05.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638300/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638300/answer","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638300/answer/previousversion/21993","Biography information for Andrew Percy","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-17","Selby-Hull Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the rejection of the proposal fort electrification of the Selby to Hull railway line on the Government's plan for a Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","53605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638301","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-24","<p>The Government is committed to its manifesto pledge to build starter homes to help young first- time buyers into home ownership. We have made strong progress on delivery, through the Housing and Planning Act, planning reforms, and working through the Homes and Communities Agency to deliver the first starter homes. We are working on a White Paper to set out our future plans for housing, including starter homes.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-24T16:30:25.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638301/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638301/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-17","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of how many starter homes the Government's starter home scheme will deliver by 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","53566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638302","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-22","<p>The English Housing Survey reports that the levels of home ownership in England in each of the last six years were:</p><ul><li>2009-10: 67%</li><li>2010-11: 66%</li><li>2011-12: 65%</li><li>2012-13: 65%</li><li>2013-14: 63%</li><li>2014-15: 64%</li></ul><p>DCLG does not publish regional data.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-22T11:55:04.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638302/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638302/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-17","Owner Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the levels of home ownership has been in (a) Coventry North East constituency, (b) Coventry, (c) the West Midlands and (d) England in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","53522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638303","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) has 30 full- and part-time staff with specific responsibilities for cyber security, which include promoting the UK cyber security industry, supporting cyber security research &amp; innovation, improving cyber security skills, ensuring the UK’s economy and society is cyber secure, engaging with EU &amp; international partners and ensuring the cyber security &amp; resilience of critical national telecommunications and Internet infrastructure. The work described above is part of the of the cross-Government national cyber security strategy and feeds into DCMS's wider remit in promoting the UK's digital economy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-23T11:50:17.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638303/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638303/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many officials of her Department have specific responsibilities for cyber security.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","53541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638304","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-25","<p>The Secretary of State appointed an Advisory Group to help inform the Government's deliberations on Charter Review. The group met six times and the Terms of Reference for the Group were published on the 12th July 2015. The Terms of Reference are available via the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445912/TERMS_OF_REFERENCE.pdf . The group members were not paid.</p><p> </p><p>Sir David Clementi was also appointed by the Secretary of State to undertake the Review of Governance and Regulation of the BBC. The Terms of Reference were published on the 1st March 2016 and are available on page 85 of the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504003/PDF_FINAL_20160224_AM_Clementi_Review.pdf . Sir David was not paid for conducting the review.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-25T13:03:16.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638304/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638304/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2016 to Question 50349, what the (a) job title and (b) specific responsibilities and associated remuneration was of the unpaid advisors that recently left her Department.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","53577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638305","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-23","<p>To date DCMS have made no assessment of the potential economic impact of the 2023 competition. Previous analysis of Liverpool's year as European Capital of Culture in 2008, carried out by the University of Liverpool and Liverpool John Moores University, can be found here: https://www.liverpool.ac.uk/media/livacuk/impacts08/pdf/pdf/Creating_an_Impact_-_web.pdf.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-23T11:56:46.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638305/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638305/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-17","European Capital of Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the potential economic effect for the cities and regions in contention for the European Capital of Culture 2023 of being in contention for that award.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","53543"
